lines.text: through the walls of my town,
and my ears hear the call
i ain't ever lived a year
then the walls of my town,
you ask where will we stand
in the winds that will howl,
as all we see will slip
so come down from your mountain
you know our breath is weak
press my nose up, to the glass
i was weaker from the start,
and i will play my bloody part.
'cause i know my weakness, know my voice,
and i'll believe in grace and choice.
and i know perhaps my heart is farce,
but i'll be born without a maa--sk.

paragraphs.text: 'cause i know that time has numbered my days. and i'll go along with everything you say. but i'll ride home laughing, look at me now. through the walls of my town, they come crumbling down.
and my ears hear the call of my unborn sons and i know their choices color all i've done. but i'll explain it all to the watchman's son, i ain't ever lived a year better spent in love.
'cause i'll know my weakness, know my voice. and i'll believe in grace and choiice. and i know perhaps my heart is farce, but i'll be born without a ma--sk.
like the city that nurtured my greed and my pride, i stretched my arms into the sky. i cry babel! babel! look at me now then the walls of my town, they come crumbling do-wwn.

you ask where will we stand in the winds that will howl, as all we see will slip into the cloud. so come down from your mountain and stand where we've been, you know our breath is weak and our body thin.
press my nose up, to the glass around your heart. i should've known i was weaker from the start,

you'll build your walls and i will play my bloody part. to tear, tear them down, well i'm gonna tear, tear them down. 'cause i know my weakness, know my voice, and i'll believe in grace and choice. and i know perhaps my heart is farce, but i'll be born without a maa--sk.
